# Why did we choose this project?

Devin and I were both extremely interested in applying machine learning
to a medical problem. Finding a humanitarian approach was important, as
we wanted to see how ML affects lives outside of a corperate
envrironment designed to create as much profit as possible(i.e. Google,
Lyft). When we searched Kaggle back in september, our eyes lit up at the
RSNA Brain Hemmorage Detection \$25,000 competition. We tried our best -
but this project was not possible for beginners such as ourselves. We
had downloaded the data to Bryce\'s home server, but was unable to
perfrom any meaningful ML operations as it lacked any form of GPU.
Uploading that dataset (600gb) to google cloud for distributed computing
would take more than a week. **We were stuck.** We had even talked to
Google Cloud representitives to see how we could accomplish this task,
but to no avail.

# So what did we do?

Determined to stick to the medical image classification task, we
searched RSNA to see if they had any projects with a reasonable size.
Luckily we did find one,
<https://www.kaggle.com/c/rsna-pneumonia-detection-challenge/overview>.

# What is Pneumonia and how is it diagnosed?

In the US, where pneumonia is a top 10 causes of death, it accounted for
over 500,000 visits to emergency departments and over 50,000 deaths in
2015.

Symptoms: Cough with phlegm or pus, fever, chills, difficult breathing

Causes: A variety of organisms, including bacteria, viruses .and fungi

Seriousness: Mild to life-threatening; it is most serious for infants
and small children, seniors, and people with weakened immune systems.

The most visible aspect of pneumonia is the intense "clouding" of the
CXR (chest radiograph).

# Why build a model?

While common, accurately diagnosing pneumonia is a difficult task and
requires years of medical training. Maybe in poorer regions, a small
hospital can only afford to employ a single Doctor with the training and
expertise required to diagnose such an ailment. The benefit of ML here
is not in terms of accuracy -- as it would always be preferred to have a
licensed professional at all stages of treatment. Rather, a ML model
doesn't require a yearly salary nor years of medical training. We hope
models such as ours and others in the medical field can potentially be
used to alleviate the workload on important hospital faculty or increase
diagnose treatment time to improve the lives of our fellow citizens.

# What needs to be done?

This is a textbook Binary-Image classification project. All the data is
labeled and the outcome is clear. Given a chest CXR can we accurately
diagnose if the patient has pneumonia? However, a more overarching goal
is present: can first time ML programmers with no formal training or
ML-focused resources produce meaningful results with TensorFlow 2.0? Is
the barrier to entry for ML as high as it seems?

This original dataset was 4gb and had about 22,000 .dicom images. The
.dicom images contained the patient metadata such as Age, weight, image
window, scale, etc. However we wanted to focus solely on the images
themselves. We used a python package called \"pydicom\" to convert about
25% of these images to jpegs. Since we ran into so many problems with
memory and cloud storage upload time, we made the choice to reduce the
total dataset by this factor so it was easier to manage. Though, it
still took multiple hours to upload and sync across our devices. Through
our iterations of our code notebooks and offline testing, this original
step isn\'t on this notebook, but this is the code we used:

# Why TensorFlow 2.0? {#why-tensorflow-20}

Released earlier this year, TF2 had been praised as a huge leap forward
in ML coding and processing. We thought this seemed like the future of
ML coding and really wanted to get our hands dirty with such a fresh
API. The documentation is beautiful, the examples are helpful, and the
community is thriving.

Originally, we were using the full-size images which is why we ran into
so many memory problems. Throughout learning and reading about this
topic it became evident that this is a bad approach. So we needed to
downsample our data and reduce the image size. As begginners to this
process, we tried to do this locally at first. We used the PIL package
to downsample the images and then save them as numpy arrays (TF2
requried numpy arrays). Again, we ran into memory problems, the program
on both my local machine and Colab failed. So we tried to split the data
up, transform, concatenate, and then save. This DID work.

However, once we loaded the data up into Google Cloud and tried to load
with np.load, we received an error because the numpy arrays had type:
object. This process took a very, very long time to figure out.
Eventually through more research we found a TF function that solved
every single problem we were having.

![image.png](data:image/png;base64,)

This would take one image at a time from the datafile, process it to our
specifications, and then put it into the ML model. Without finding this
function, our project might have never taken off.
:::

\#The original model: We chose a feed-forward CNN as per your advice.
Orginally Bryce introduced the project to you during office hours and
you said a feed-forward CNN would suffice and the extra compelxity Bryce
had in mind was not neccessary. You (Dr.Lee) were absolutely correct and
saved us alot of time if we were to go a different direction.

On TF2.0 documentation and on Stackoverflow answers, most everyone
agreed Relu activation fucntion was the best for this sort of model with
sigmoid for the final layer. We do not know the specifcs of why these
activators work better in certain scenarios, but we were not in a
position to question why as this setup worked well for us.
:::

::: {.cell .code execution_count="0" colab="{}" colab_type="code" id="LdnyxRCtdzvC"}
``` {.python}
model = Sequential([
    Conv2D(16, 3, padding='same', activation='relu', input_shape=(IMG_HEIGHT, IMG_WIDTH ,3)),
    MaxPooling2D(),
    Conv2D(32, 3, padding='same', activation='relu'),
    MaxPooling2D(),
    Conv2D(64, 3, padding='same', activation='relu'),
    MaxPooling2D(),
    Flatten(),
    Dense(512, activation='relu'),
    Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')
])
```
:::

\#Callbacks

Callbacks are a sort of extra functionality that can be added to your
Model.

Bryce had heard about the \"TensorBoard API\"(Below, but only active if
the Kernel is Active) which allows you to view and modify parameters
inside a visual suite and compare it with different versions of your
model.

This is how the Epoch Graphs and Model layouts were created in our
powerpoint.

The \"Early Stop\" callback would stop the model once it plateaus or if
it detects extreme overfitting. Hence, our final model stopped at 12
epochs rather than the 15 specified.
:::

::: {.cell .code execution_count="0" colab="{}" colab_type="code" id="3UE960zGhLfN"}


::: {.cell .markdown colab_type="text" id="Gq01r2VD92L3"}
\#Clear Overfitting This is obvious overfitting, we started the first
epoch with 95% accuracy(odd) and for every epoch after, the Validation
Accuracy and Loss continued to worsen. Our model was well equipt to
handle the training data, but was not generalized enough to perform well
on a smaller, new dataset.

Obviously this is terrible and unreliable, as with Binary
classification, 50% is the baseline\... a random guess. If 3/10 patients
are being misdiagnosed then we are doing more harm than good.
:::

::: {.cell .markdown colab_type="text" id="b--w3tM_BbSy"}
# How we adressed overfitting: Dataset

First, we wanted to make our training dataset more generalized.

We randomly applied up to a 30% zoom, a horizontal flip, up to 30
degrees of rotation and up to 10 pixels of width and height
tranformations.

The patient is not restrained in a CXR like one would be in a MRI. So
many images might have some rotation variance. Additionally, the patient
may be smaller, larger, or a different distance from the CXR device
itself, so we hoped the zoom would account for that. The horizontal flip
and X,Y shift were also possible, we thought.
:::

::: {.cell .code execution_count="0" colab="{}" colab_type="code" id="c5_23LlyFg7I"}
``` {.python}
image_gen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1./255, horizontal_flip=True)
```

::: {.cell .markdown colab_type="text" id="qocrzcryDyQF"}
\#How we addressed Overfitting: The model

\#Dropout Layers So, a dropout layer will randomly kill a percentage of
the neurons in that layer(we chose 20%) our hope is that the
classification information would be better spread across more neurons
this way, so that the same patterns of activation couldn\'t be
consistent onr training step to the next. We really didn\'t know where
to put these layers, so we just chose a Conv2D Layer and one of the
Dense layers. It seemed to work well, but more prototyping with this
might have yeilded better results.

\#Regularlizers This gives a penalty to high-firing neurons. So if a
neuron would continue to fire with high intensity every training step,
it effect would be penalized. Again- we hoped that this would better
spread the classification information across more neurons.
:::

::: {.cell .code execution_count="0" colab="{}" colab_type="code" id="6cHFN29iGi7S"}
``` {.python}
model_new = Sequential([
    Conv2D(16, 3, padding='same', activation='relu', 
           input_shape=(IMG_HEIGHT, IMG_WIDTH ,3)),
    MaxPooling2D(),
    Dropout(0.2), #Dropout 1
    Conv2D(32, 3, padding='same', activation='relu'),
    MaxPooling2D(),
    Conv2D(64, 3, padding='same', kernel_regularizer=keras.regularizers.l2(0.001), activation='relu'), #L2 Regularizer 1
    MaxPooling2D(),
    Dropout(0.2), #Dropout 2
    Flatten(),
    Dense(512, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=keras.regularizers.l2(0.001)), #L2 Regularizer 2
    Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')
])
```
:::

``` {.python}
model_new.compile(optimizer='adam',
              loss='binary_crossentropy',
              metrics=['accuracy'])

model_new.summary()
```

\#Results

This was much much much better than our original model. Here we can see
pairwise increase of accuracy and decrease of loss. Additionally, both
training and testing converged to around 88%.

Though still not accurate enough for widespread use or true application,
we felt this was a great result for our first try at ML classification
and a great example of the power that TF2.0 holds. With a larger
dataset, longer training time, more prototyping, and proper equiptment,
we are sure that this 88% result could be in the high 90\'s.
:::

\#Conclusion

This was an incredibly exciting and intresting project for us. We were
able to create a model that guessed if a patient had pneumonia about
9/10 times.

Additionally, we learned so much about how little we actaully know. We
came into this project incredibly ambitious and got destroyed by our
blissful ignorance. Thankfully, everything worked out in the end but we
went through a long process of intense troubleshooting.

Though this final notebook reflects rather direct and simple coding(due
to TF2.0) the process of getting to this point is what we are most proud
of - there are far more cells that have been deleted than are being
shown.

We learned it is possible for anyone to get started into the modern
space of ML via TensorFlow2.0 and the knowledge we gained during this
projcect has already already altered our daily workflow.

As a statistics major, I(Bryce) never was taught to optimize code for
time and space complexity, but I was forced to learn these topics to
complete this project as my hardware couldnt handle what I was telling
it to do.

Additionally, I (Bryce) had never even used cloud storage before this
project, now all of my files are clearly labeled and synced across all
my devices. I realzied the importance of clearly labeling files and NOT
overwritting my work in addtion to all the Machine Learning tactics.
This project forced me not only to organize my digital space, but my
life as a whole and I am extremly thankful for that.

Version Control and Collaboration was also a topic we became extremly
familiar with, as it was the only way we could work on the same file
simutaneously.

Although there are so many more advancements that could be made even to
this project, (RNN, More layers, more data, etc.) we beleive we have
demonstrated a baseline to any one else that wants to get started in
this field. It **IS** possible if you KEEP MOVING FORWARD and not
letting errors stop you!

The Code was written by me(Bryce) and this writeup as well. Devin
completed the proposals and formatted the presentations as per my
instructions. I am not dissapointed at all in the division of labor
because from the beginning I told Devin that I would focus on the code
since this required my desktop while Devin only has a macbook laptop.
Additionally, Devin did most of the background research on pneumonia
(and originally the Brain Hemooraging). Since there wasn\'t a clear EDA
phase(just .jpegs) other than train/test split and things like image
size there wasnt a good way to split this code up between us. It would
have been difficult to keep us both moving at the same pace since this
was such a new topic for both of us and went beyond the scope of our
homework. However, Devin always was asking me to explain what was going
on and to help if he could. I am very pleased with the contribution
split, especially given our other member dropped the class.
:::
